content.text:
The issue was that when the percentage increase is infinite (i.e., previous value was 0), the app displayed `(∞)`. The requirement was to only show the increase (e.g., `+1`) without the percentage.

I analyzed `WordPress/src/main/java/org/wordpress/android/ui/stats/refresh/utils/StatsUtils.kt` and found that `buildChange` function constructs the string. It was using `R.string.stats_traffic_increase` which includes the percentage: `+%1$s (%2$s)`.

I implemented the fix by:
1.  Adding a new string resource `stats_traffic_increase_infinity` with value `+%1$s` in `WordPress/src/main/res/values/strings.xml`.
2.  Modifying `StatsUtils.kt` to check if the calculated percentage is `"∞"`. If so, it uses the new string resource to display only the formatted difference with a positive sign, omitting the percentage.

I attempted to verify the changes with a new test file, but the project's build environment seems to have pre-existing issues (missing resources in the vanilla debug variant) preventing the tests from running. However, the logic is straightforward and I verified it through static analysis of the code and resources.

**Changes:**

1.  Modified `WordPress/src/main/res/values/strings.xml`:
    Added `<string name="stats_traffic_increase_infinity">+%1$s</string>`

2.  Modified `WordPress/src/main/java/org/wordpress/android/ui/stats/refresh/utils/StatsUtils.kt`:
    Updated `buildChange` method:
    ```kotlin
            if (positive) {
                if (percentage == "∞") {
                    resourceProvider.getString(R.string.stats_traffic_increase_infinity, formattedDifference)
                } else {
                    resourceProvider.getString(R.string.stats_traffic_increase, formattedDifference, percentage)
                }
            } else {
                resourceProvider.getString(R.string.stats_traffic_change, formattedDifference, percentage)
            }
    ```

